# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1932-winter-olympics-medal-table
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1896 Summer Olympics, officially known as the Games of the I Olympiad, were a summer multi-sport event held in Athens, the capital of Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896, and were the first Olympic Games of the Modern era.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 241 athletes from 14 nations participated in 43 events in nine sports at these games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, and three medals were won by mixed teams, i.e., teams made up of athletes from multiple nations.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The United States won the most gold medals (11) with 14 athletes participating.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] In contrast, the host nation, Greece, with 169 athletes participating, won the most medals overall (47) as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one less gold medal than the United States, having 155 athletes more than the U.S.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] In the early Olympic Games, several team events were contested by athletes from multiple nations.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Retroactively, the IOC created the designation "Mixed team" (with the country code ZZX) to refer to this group of athletes.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Some athletes won medals individually and as part of a mixed team, so these medals are tabulated under different nations in the official counts.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Dionysios Kasdaglis, an athlete of Greek origins living in Alexandria, Egypt, is listed by the IOC as Greek during both his competition in the singles tennis competition and the doubles tennis competition along with his teammate, the Greek athlete Demetrios Petrokokkinos.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] During these inaugural Olympics, winners were given a silver medal and an olive branch, while runners-up received a copper medal and a laurel branch.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best-placed athletes in each event to comply with more recent traditions.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Three ties resulted in athletes sharing medals, increasing the medal count of various nations.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] In addition, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown – two in swimming and three in gymnastics – and several events had no third-place finisher.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] This is the full table of the medal count of the 1896 Summer Olympics, based on the International Olympic Committee (IOC) medal count.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] Some sources, besides the International Olympic Committee (IOC), that display variations in the medal totals, but as the governing body of the Olympic Games, the IOC is considered the most authoritative source for this article.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] These rankings are sorted by the number of gold medals a country earns.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The number of silver medals is considered next, and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given, and they are listed alphabetically.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1896-summer-olympics-medal-table] The IOC provides this information; however, the IOC does not recognise or endorse any ranking system.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1900 Summer Olympics, now officially known as the Games of the II Olympiad, were an international multi-sport event held in Paris, France, from May 14 to October 28, 1900, as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 1,226 athletes representing 26 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The games featured 95 events in 19 sports.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Archery, Basque pelota, cricket, croquet, equestrian jumping, football, golf, polo, rugby union, rowing, sailing, tug of war, and water polo were contested for the first time at these Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Women competed in the Olympics for the first time during the 1900 games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Athletes representing 19 NOCs received at least one medal.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] France won the most of every type of medal, while the United States won the second-most of every type of medal.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Spain, Cuba, the Netherlands, Italy, and Belgium all won their nation's first Olympic gold medals.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Belgium, Italy, Netherlands, Cuba, Spain, Norway, India, Bohemia, and Sweden all won their nation's first Olympic medals of any kind.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] During the 1900 games, athletes participating in mixed teams won medals in football, polo, rowing, tennis, and tug of war.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Gilt silver medals were awarded for first place in shooting, lifesaving, motor racing, and gymnastics, while second place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, sailing, tennis, gymnastics, fencing, equestrian, and athletics.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Third place bronze medals were awarded in gymnastics, firefighting, and shooting.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] However, in many sports, medals were not awarded, with most of the listed prizes being cups and other similar trophies.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver, and bronze medals to competitors who earned first, second, and third place finishes in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Alvin Kraenzlein won four gold medals at the 1900 Summer Olympics, the most of any competing athlete.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Prizes worth a total of 953,448 francs were awarded to the athletes across the competitions.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Various cash prizes and art objects were awarded to the athletes.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] In addition, medals and plaques were distributed, including the sports plaque designed by Frédéric de Vernon, available in gilt silver, silver, or bronze.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Produced by Monnaie de Paris, the medal features two sides.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] On the front, a winged goddess holds laurel branches high above her head, with Paris and the grand monuments of the Universal Exhibition visible in the background.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] On the reverse, a victorious athlete stands proudly on a podium, raising a laurel branch in his right hand.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] Behind him, a stadium and the Acropolis of Athens serve as a reminder of the deep connection between ancient and modern Olympic traditions.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The medal table is based on information provided by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and is consistent with IOC conventional sorting in its published medal tables.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The table uses the Olympic medal table sorting method.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won, where a nation is an entity represented by a NOC.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1900-summer-olympics-medal-table] If teams are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by their IOC country code.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1904 Summer Olympics were held in St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] Louis, Missouri, United States from July 1 to November 23, 1904, as part of the St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 651 athletes from 12 nations participated in 95 events in 16 sports at these games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] Nine participating nations earned medals, in addition to four medals won by mixed teams.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] Retroactively, the IOC created the designation "mixed team" (with the country code ZZX) to refer to these groups of athletes.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] Some athletes won medals both individually and as part of a mixed team, so these medals are tabulated under different nations in the official counts.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] The United States won 231 medals, setting a record that still stands today.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] The Soviet Union came closest to beating the record with 195 medals at the 1980 Summer Olympics and currently is in second place.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] The Soviets, however, won a record 80 gold medals, surpassing 76 golds won by the Americans in 1904.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] However, the United States subsequently won 83 gold medals in the 1984 Summer Olympics, setting another all-time record.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] Gold medals were awarded to event winners for the first time at the 1904 games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1904-summer-olympics-medal-table] Prior to that, a silver medal was awarded to first-place finishers and a bronze medal to second-place finishers.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1908 Summer Olympics (also known as the Games of the IV Olympiad) was an international multi-sport event held from 27 April to 31 October 1908, in London, United Kingdom, coinciding with the Franco-British Exhibition.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 2,008 athletes representing 22 nations participated in 110 events in 18 sports.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] Diving, field hockey, and figure skating were contested for the first time at these Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] Argentina, Switzerland and Turkey were the only nations that did not earn any medals.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] The host nation, the United Kingdom, with by far the most competitors, dominated the medal table, collecting the most gold (56), silver (51), and bronze (39) medals.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 146 medals won at these Games—a major increase from the two medals won at the 1904 Summer Olympics in St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] Louis—are still the highest number won by a British delegation at any modern Olympics.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] Particular success was achieved by the British team in the boxing events, where out of a possible fifteen medals across the five weight classes, they won all but the middleweight silver medal, which was taken by Reginald Baker competing for Australasia.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] The United States finished second in the medal standings, and Sweden third.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] Australasia was the name given to the combined team of athletes from Australia (making its fourth Olympic appearance) and New Zealand (competing for the first time).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] The host team included a number of athletes from Ireland, at the time part of the United Kingdom.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] In contrast, Finland, which was integrated in the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] This is the full table of the medal count of the 1908 Summer Olympics, based on the medal count of the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] These rankings sort by the number of gold medals earned by a country.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1908-summer-olympics-medal-table] This information is provided by the IOC; however the IOC does not recognize or endorse any ranking system.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1912 Summer Olympics, officially known as the Games of the V Olympiad, were an international multi-sport event held in Stockholm, Sweden, between 5 May and 27 July 1912.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] A total of 2,407 athletes representing 28 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated, which included seven teams making their Olympic debut at the Summer Games; Chile, Egypt, Iceland, Japan, Luxembourg, Portugal, and Serbia.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] The games featured 107 events in 19 disciplines.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] The games included the Olympic debut of equestrian dressage and eventing, as well as the modern pentathlon.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Athletes representing 19 NOCs received at least one medal, with 16 winning at least one gold medal.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Sweden won the most medals overall, with 65, while the United States won the most gold medals, with 44.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Among individual participants, Swedish shooter Vilhelm Carlberg, Finnish runner Hannes Kolehmainen, and American shooter Alfred Lane tied for the most gold medals, with three each.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Carlberg had the most total medals, with five (three gold, two silver).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] The 1912 Games featured five art competitions which awarded medals, but did not do so for a full top three, instead opting to award only a first or first and second place medal.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Only gold and no silver or bronze medals were awarded in architecture, literature, music, and painting.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] In sculpturing, a gold and silver medal, but no bronze, were awarded.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] In the men's light heavyweight Greco-Roman, the final round featured three wrestlers, Anders Ahlgren, Ivar Böhling, and Béla Varga, who took turns facing off against one another.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Ahlgren and Böhling defeated Varga, but they were unable to defeat each other.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] The match between Ahlgren and Böhling lasted for over 9 hours without a victor.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] The Olympic rules at the time specifically stated that the winner must have beaten their opponent, and since neither person could claim to have done so, both Ahlgreen and Böhling were awarded silver medals, with no gold being awarded.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] In men's single sculls and men's coxed four, there were two-way ties for third which resulted in two bronze medals being awarded in each event.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] In men's pole vault, there was a two-way tie for second, which resulted in two silver medals being awarded.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Additionally, there was a three-way tie for fourth, which the IOC awarded bronze medals for.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] In the tug of war, three of the five teams withdrew for unknown reasons, resulting in only two teams participating and a bronze medal not being awarded.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1912-summer-olympics-medal-table] Three teams made the final round of the men's 4 x 100 metres relay, but when Germany was disqualified for a faulty baton pass, it resulted in no bronze medal being awarded for the event.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Olympiade***) and commonly known as **Antwerp 1920** (French: ***Anvers 1920***; Dutch and German: ***Antwerpen 1920***), were an international multi-sport event held in 1920 in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] In March 1912, during the 13th session of the IOC, Belgium's bid to host the 1920 Summer Olympics was made by Baron Édouard de Laveleye, president of the Belgian Olympic Committee and of the Royal Belgian Football Association.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] No fixed host city was proposed at the time.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The 1916 Summer Olympics, to have been held in Berlin, capital of the German Empire, were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] When the Olympic Games resumed after the war, Antwerp was awarded the hosting rights to the 1920 Summer Games as a tribute to the Belgian people.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The aftermath of the war and the Paris Peace Conference affected the Olympic Games not only due to new states being created but also by sanctions against the nations that lost the war and were blamed for starting it.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Hungary, Germany, Austria, Bulgaria, and the Ottoman Empire were banned from competing in the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Soviet Russia had just emerged from the Civil War and chose not to attend the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Germany did not return to Olympic competition until 1928 and instead hosted a series of games called Deutsche Kampfspiele, starting with the Winter edition of 1922 (which predated the first Winter Olympics).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold and overall medals at the 1920 Summer Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] In March 1912, during the 13th session of the IOC, the bid on behalf of Belgium to host the 1920 Summer Olympics was made by Baron Édouard de Laveleye, president of the Belgian Olympic Committee and of the Royal Belgian Football Association.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The organizing committee was created on 9 August 1913.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Among the 22 vice presidents of the committee were people with a military or industrial background and further people from sports organizations, like Paul Havenith, president of the football and athletics club K.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Beerschot V.A.C., and Nicolaas Jan Cupérus, president of the Belgian Gymnastics Federation.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The first action of the committee was to send an official letter to the IOC in Paris, confirming Antwerp as the city for the Belgian Olympic bid.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] With Antwerp confirmed as the Olympic Games host, Belgium began reconstructing the Beerschot Stadium into the Olympisch Stadion.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Construction on the new Olympic stadium began in July 1919 and finished in May 1920.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] In 1914, a 109-page brochure was created to promote the idea of Antwerp as a host city for the Olympics: *Aurons-nous la VIIème Olympiade à Anvers?* (*Will we have the 7th Olympiad at Antwerp?*).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] It was sent to all IOC members and was used during the 6th Olympic Congress in Paris in 1914, where the candidacies of Amsterdam (which would eventually host the 1928 Summer Olympics), Antwerp, Budapest, and Rome (which would eventually host the 1960 Summer Olympics) were discussed.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Despite a slight preference at the time for Budapest, no final choice was made, and the outbreak of World War I soon afterwards prevented any further progress.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] In 1915, Lyon made a bid for the 1920 Games, but after some discussion, they agreed to support Antwerp and postpone their bid until 1924 if Antwerp was liberated in time to organize the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The support for Belgium by cousin country France, then the leading country of the IOC, also meant that Amsterdam and Budapest (in an enemy state) had no chance for the 1920 games against Antwerp.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] New candidacies from American cities did not have that disadvantage, and bids were received from Cleveland, Philadelphia, and Atlanta (which would eventually host the 1996 Summer Olympics), while Cuba also submitted a bid for Havana.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] However, shortly after the armistice in November 1918, the IOC decided to award Antwerp their first preference if they were still willing to host the 1920 Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] In March 1919, the Belgian Olympic Committee decided to go ahead with the organization of the Games: on 5 April 1919, at a meeting in Lausanne, Antwerp was officially declared the host city for the games of the VIIth Olympiad.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The 1920 Summer Games organizers had very little time to prepare.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The time between the IOC's decision of choosing Antwerp as the host city and the opening ceremony was 1 year, 4 months, and 9 days, making this the shortest time for a host city to plan and organize an Olympic edition.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] An executive committee was established on 17 April 1919, with Henri de Baillet-Latour as chairman and Alfred Verdyck, the secretary of the Belgian Union of Football Clubs, as general secretary.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Seven commissions were created to deal with finances, accommodation, press relations, propaganda, schedules, transport, and festivities.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Finances and scheduling proved to be the two hardest parts to tackle: the program of events was not published until February 1920, six months before the official start of the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Between 23 and 30 April 1920, an ice hockey tournament marked the early start of the Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Held in the "Palais de Glace" or Ice Palace in Antwerp, it was the first time that ice hockey was an Olympic sport.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The first stone of the new Olympisch Stadion was laid on 4 July 1919 by Jan De Vos, mayor of Antwerp, and inaugurated less than a year later on 23 May 1920 with a gymnastics demonstration.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] When the Olympic Games began, the stadium was still unfinished, with some events being built over fortifications and others using existing locations.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The athletes' quarters were crowded, and athletes slept on folding cots.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The nautical stadium, or Stade Nautique d'Antwerp, was built at the end of the Jan Van Rijswijcklaan, using the city ramparts there as a spectator's stand.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Other events, like shooting, boxing, and equestrian sports, were held at pre-existing locations in and around Antwerp and as far away as Ostend.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The number of spectators was low throughout Antwerp's Summer Olympics because few people could afford tickets.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] In the closing days of the Olympic Games, students were allowed to attend the event for free.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] After the conclusion of the Olympic Games, Belgium recorded a loss of more than 600 million francs.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] There were 162 events in 28 disciplines that were part of the Olympic program in 1920.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Women's water polo was a demonstration sport.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The 1920 Summer Olympics featured seventeen sports venues.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that the football tournament was spread throughout the country, which has mostly been the case since.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] A total of 29 nations participated in the Antwerp Games, only one more than in 1912, as Germany, Austria, Hungary, Bulgaria, and Turkey were not invited, having lost World War I and sanctioned for starting it.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] From the newly created European states, only Estonia took part, as Czechoslovakia succeeded Bohemia and the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes succeeded Serbia, with both nations having sent athletes prior to World War I (in the case of Bohemia, as part of the Austrian Empire).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Soviet Russia was busy with the Polish-Soviet War and therefore was unable to form an Olympic team (Poland, in turn, had never participated in the games before, only doing so in later editions).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Brazil and Monaco competed as nations at the Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] New Zealand, which had competed as part of a combined team with Australia in 1908 and 1912, competed on its own for the first time.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The games marked the return of Argentina and India to the competitions.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] At the time, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, India, and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] Egypt was a British protectorate (a state not part of the British Empire but nonetheless administered by the United Kingdom).
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] As the local Olympic Organizing Committee went bankrupt during the Antwerp 1920 Games, no official report of the Games was ever produced.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] The documents of the Games were archived at the Belgium Olympic Committee headquarters in Brussels.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1920 Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1920-summer-olympics] These were the first Olympics where the host nation failed to win the most medals overall.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The 1932 Winter Olympics, officially known as the III Olympic Winter Games, were an international multi-sport event held in Lake Placid, New York, United States, from February 4 to 15, 1932.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] A total of 252 athletes representing 17 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated, 8 NOCs fewer than the last Winter Games in St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The games featured 14 events in 4 sports across 7 disciplines.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] These Winter Games were the first held outside Europe, with prior editions held in Chamonix, France, and St.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Overall, athletes representing 10 NOCs won at least one medal, and 7 NOCs won at least one gold medal.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Host nation United States won the most gold medals and the most overall medals, with 6 and 12 respectively.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Hungary's team obtained their first Winter Olympic medal, with figure skaters Emília Rotter and László Szollás winning bronze in the pair skating event.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Speed skaters Irving Jaffee and Jack Shea, both from the United States, tied for the most gold medals won for an individual at the games, with two.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Shea became the first American athlete to win multiple gold medals at the same Olympic Winter Games.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Alongside Jaffee and Shea, cross-country skier Veli Saarinen of Finland and speed skaters Alexander Hurd and Willy Logan of Canada tied for the most total medals won with two each.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The medals used for the 1932 Winter Olympics were minted by the Robbins Company.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The obverse of the medals featured a design of a goddess holding a laurel wreath behind the Adirondack Mountains.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] It also featured the host city's landscape with a stadium and a ski jumping hill.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The reverse of the medals featured the Olympic rings, the official name of the games, and a laurel wreath.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The medal itself had curved ridges that were said to represent ancient Greek columns.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] For the first time in Olympic history, medals awarded to athletes were given out on podiums.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] The podiums were based on the medal awarding of the athletics events at the 1930 British Empire Games in Hamilton, Canada, where winning athletes stood on top of a podium while the second- and third-placed athletes stood on their sides, one step below.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Then-president of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), Henri de Baillet-Latour, saw the practice and developed his own version.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Instructions to use De Baillet-Latour's version of the practice were sent out by the IOC to the organizing committees of the 1932 Summer Olympics and 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1932-winter-olympics-medal-table/1932-winter-olympics-medal-table] Shea became the first Olympic champion to be awarded a medal on top of a podium after winning the gold medal at the men's 500 metres event in speed skating.
